&gt;&gt; CATHERINE HIEBERT KERST: He.

00:59:08.350 --> 00:59:09.720
Mr. Biotical [assumed
spelling], he's Croatian,

00:59:09.720 --> 00:59:12.060
I don't remember exactly
where he was from.

00:59:12.060 --> 00:59:17.830
But I mean she recorded a
wide variety of instruments

00:59:17.830 --> 00:59:21.860
that were unfamiliar to a
lot of people in California.

00:59:21.860 --> 00:59:27.250
Then the three middle women are
the three Puerto Rican woman

00:59:27.250 --> 00:59:29.440
who were friends and
who were all recorded

00:59:29.440 --> 00:59:32.370
at Arura Caldron's
[assumed spelling] home.

00:59:32.370 --> 00:59:36.240
I've actually located
Arura Caldron's daughter

00:59:36.240 --> 00:59:37.820
who is still in Oakland.

00:59:37.820 --> 00:59:43.900
So, I love having those
connections because from that era,

00:59:43.900 --> 00:59:49.190
we're moving away from people
who might be able to be located.

00:59:49.190 --> 00:59:50.490
Yes.

00:59:50.490 --> 00:59:52.030
&gt;&gt; And one more question.

00:59:52.030 --> 00:59:57.400
The Lomax recordings, did she?

00:59:57.400 --> 01:00:00.450
It sounds like, I wouldn't
say collaborated,

01:00:00.450 --> 01:00:03.040
but she fed ideas to him?

01:00:03.040 --> 01:00:09.280
Did she actually ever go to
Appalachia and record with Lomax,

01:00:09.280 --> 01:00:12.840
and that's kind of what I wanted,
is there any cross stuff going

01:00:12.840 --> 01:00:14.540
on between them as far

01:00:14.540 --> 01:00:20.700
as collaborating, you
know recording, or?

01:00:20.700 --> 01:00:24.860
&gt;&gt; CATHERINE HIEBERT
KERST: Not with Alan Lomax.

01:00:24.860 --> 01:00:29.510
Sidney went on a recording,
on a little field trip

01:00:29.510 --> 01:00:36.050
with Frank C. Brown and John
Lomax, Alan Lomax's father in 1936.

01:00:36.050 --> 01:00:39.070
And that was where she
was sort of testing

01:00:39.070 --> 01:00:42.100
out how well she could
work the recording machine

01:00:42.100 --> 01:00:44.570
for Resettlement Administration.

01:00:44.570 --> 01:00:48.750
But otherwise I don't believe
that Robertson ever recorded

01:00:48.750 --> 01:00:53.350
with Alan Lomax, though they
were very aware of each other.

01:00:53.350 --> 01:00:59.740
And I mean he would have a radio
program in New York and say,

01:00:59.740 --> 01:01:04.720
oh do you have any 49'ers
songs that I could play on the?

01:01:04.720 --> 01:01:07.300
You know so they were colleagues

01:01:07.300 --> 01:01:14.250
and their relationship was
a little thorny sometimes,

01:01:14.250 --> 01:01:21.250
but I think they both respected
each other in a certain way.

01:01:21.250 --> 01:01:23.570
Yes?

01:01:23.570 --> 01:01:26.750
&gt;&gt; Seems like mostly
European extraction,

01:01:26.750 --> 01:01:29.180
did she do any Asian recording?

01:01:29.180 --> 01:01:30.480
&gt;&gt; CATHERINE HIEBERT KERST: No.

01:01:30.480 --> 01:01:32.830
There are a few scale drawings,

01:01:32.830 --> 01:01:37.310
blueprints of some Chinese
instruments because she had planned

01:01:37.310 --> 01:01:40.430
that they would be done
in the second phase,

01:01:40.430 --> 01:01:42.460
though I think it might have
been really hard for her

01:01:42.460 --> 01:01:45.900
because of her lack of knowing
any other those languages,

01:01:45.900 --> 01:01:49.120
though it would have
been fascinating.

01:01:54.550 --> 01:01:55.850
Well thank you.

01:01:55.850 --> 01:01:57.650
Thank you so much.

